description.text:
This is a simple cooler for the ASUS RT-AC88U Router.

They are known to run a bit warm, so I made this using a spare blower fan I have a bunch of laying around (Harvested from equipment.) I tried a few variations, this one is simple and does a good job. I think part of the reason is it fits the top vent of the router closely and keeps a good draft through the unit without being obnoxiously loud.

Designed using the Delta BFB0512m fan model from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2078835.

In testing, this took my CPU from 80C to 58C in about 40 minutes in a warm room.

In a second test, I let it soak in a 30C room (86F) most of the day and CPU reached 61C (146F), consistently keeps the CPU about 20C under ambient.

I think it would also fit the RT-AC3100, but DO NOT KNOW THIS FOR A FACT. If someone wants to try and let me know, that'd be awesome. :)

title: Easier to fit Rocksolid IPhone Bumper

description.text:
**Updated stl to an improved model***
It's an improved version on previously made Rocksolid IPhone 4 Bumper.

Instruction Video
http://youtu.be/KZPcZmigoQw Print with PLA. You can use supplied G-code or make some adjust if you wish. READ INSTRUCTIONS BEFORE USING WARNING : There is almost no space between the phone and the bumper and requires some force to fit so be careful not to break anything such as power button, vibrate switch, your finger or IPhone. Print with fill greater than 80%, I've done with 100%. Otherwise horizontal layers won't stick well at thinner parts. Now the important part - Watch the instruction video

  • Lay down the bumper and IPhone with the back panel up and volume/vibrate buttons facing away from you.

  • Bottom left corner of the bumper (after step 1, bottom left corner is now on the right and facing towards you) has reduced overhang. Now lay the bumper down and fit your IPhone from up(as in from the air). Fit and align 3 other corners very tight.

  • Slowly push in the bottom left corner until it's in place. You should hear a "click" sound. Make sure other 3 corners are still in place. Check the screen side(front) as well.

  • If it doesn't make its way easy then tap it with your hand gently but firmly. It may require some force to push in. Once it's in, it should feel rock solid.

  • To take it off, hold your IPhone and push the bottom left corner from the back to the front, with both thumb until it pops out. Once it's been in and out, it should be easier to fit.

This is my first THING after 1 year of owning my Da Vinci Pro 1.0 (I got lazy and really did not use my 3D printer as my projects did not require to show a 3D model). Daughter was pushing me to make some Pokemon so I ended up using all of my ABS and I have a box load of PLA so I have no choice but to do the fan mod now.

After looking at various fan mounts and studying them in 3D I decided to make my own as I found that there are a few things that will make the various mounts not work on my machine and the fact that I want to create my own and share it. My reasons are:

  • Somehow the front end of the extruder holder has 3 screws poking out facing the printer door. All of the mounts I saw did not allow for this.

  • There are various blower fan designs and sizes that you can buy and the housing is always different. My mount can mount a 50mm down to 30mm or smaller if there is such a fan that small. I also want to be able to adjust it or slide it for better precision on where it is exactly blowing but not directly on the nozzle. There is a mount that I saw that pivots only where you secure the blower fan but it is only for a single fan design.

  • I want a simpler design so that it will be lighter for the extruder carriage. I also do not want a switch on the extruder as well and I want fan RPM control (my next mod). So right now the only way I can turn the fan on and off is with a JST connector that I took from my RC box.

This is what I did:

  • Print the mount to .2mm and at 100% Infill. with supports (low). I just used the XYZ slicer. Took 2.5 hours to print for 2 mounts.

  • I used 4-40 1" machine screws and nuts with washers to secure the blower fan to the mount.

  • I bought 2 blower fans similar to this (12V). Why 12v? so that I can use a PC fan controller to control the speed of the fan. Make sure it is not more than 15mm thick or it won't fit on this mount.

http://www.ebay.com/itm/12V-0-14A-Blower-Cooling-Fan-5015-50x50x15mm-RepRap-3D-Printer-Extruder-PLA-50mm-/261816986831?hash=item3cf5822ccf

  • I used super strong 3M automotive mounting tape to mount it on the extruder housing (no super glue, no zip ties). Put it on the back and bottom of the mount.

https://www.amazon.com/3M-03609-Scotch-Mount-Molding-Tape/dp/B000BO913C/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1502165694&sr=8-1&keywords=3m+super+strong+automotive+attachment+tape

  • Mount it on the extruder housing as per the pictures.

  • Provide power to the fans (external supplied or from the printer it self).

TIP:

  • Make sure to heat up the extruder a few times to set the adhesive of the tape. I recommend not to use the printer for 24 hours just to be safe that it wont de-laminate.

  • Make sure the fan you use is not more than 15mm thick or it will not fit. If your fan is different than what I used and you want to change the angle of the nozzle just use one screw (secure it on the top portion of the fan) then just slide up and down while tilting the blower fan to change the direction of the air flow. Just make sure the bottom of your fan will not be lower than your extruder tip or you will be scraping your fan to your print bed or prints (BE WARNED!)

  • Make sure to use stranded wires (not solid) when wiring your fans. 22 gauge is more than enough. Stranded wires is recommended when the wires will be moving which is exactly what will happen on the 3D printer. Amazon or Ebay is your friend to find this wire if you do not have a local hobby shop or low voltage shop near by.

  • Insulate all your splices. Grab a heat shrink wrap and wrap all your exposed wiring connections. Ask experienced people here on what to do and how to do it if you are sourcing your power inside the printer. You do not want a $700 paper weight in the end.

  • If using this to print PLA do not turn on the fan on the first 2 layers or the PLA won't stick on the print bed.

I want to thank ChatToBrian for the inspiration of this design as I used his fan mount as the basis of my design. Thank you Brian again for the info on the wiring of the Da Vinci Pro.

https://youtu.be/UlDCoKT0igc

title: CR-10 hanging fan/part cooler for stock, Microswiss and E3D v6 hotends

description.text:
Updates :

2018-03-20
1) Finally tested the e3d mount, updated bracket to mount flush against the plate to eliminate possible wiggle

2018-02-22
1) Official E3D v6 mount and bracket developed in collaboration with ficador

2018-02-19
1) Experimental E3D v6 mount and bracket
2) Fixed height bracket

2018-01-21
1) Merged dual 30 here as they share most parts: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2641456
2) Reorganize files, remove old versions, new version starts at 10

Features :

1) Hotend mounts directly to carriage using original hardware
2) Choice of single 40mm or dual 30mm part cooler fan
3) 2 piece bracket for easy install, bracket holds both stock and Microswiss all metal hotends, separate bracket for E3D v6
4) Duct and fans can be removed without also removing the hotend
5) With fan and duct out of the way, thermistor and heater are easily accessible

Printing :

1) Parts can be printed without supports, snap off supports already added to ducts
2) Fan case accommodates 12.5mm thick fans (Noctua 40x10), cut it in your slicer if you want 10mm or use appropriate washer. Same thing applies to the single 40mm duct.
3) Print ducts at 0.16 or higher resolution
4) PLA works fine, but more heat resistant filaments are better

Fan CFM:

CFM, RPM and static pressure usually are directly proportional.
For the 40mm, use a fan that's capable of delivering between 5 to 12 CFM.
For the dual 30mm, use 3 to 6 CFM each.

Note : using too high a CFM fan/s may result in "THERMAL RUNAWAY" error

Installation :

1) Assemble hotend, bracket_end and bracket face, use 2 m3 12-16mm bolt, see picture as reference for correct bracket orientation
2) Mount assembly to x carriage using original bolt and lock washer
3) Assemble blower fan, fan grill/guard and duct, use 4 m3 18mm bolt to secure the fan and grill to the duct
4) Assemble front fan case, front fan and fan guard, insert 2 m3 30mm bolt through fan mounting holes, fan cables should stick out on top. Bolts at the upper-left and lower-right gives you low clearance from the bed, upper-right and lower-left high clearance, note that this depends on how the bracket was mounted
5) Mount assembled fan case through the assembled duct to the bracket.
6) Connect your wires

ABL Mounts :

See this make : https://www.thingiverse.com/make:399987

Recommended mount by ficador:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2785339

Alternative mounts:
https://www.th3dstudio.com/knowledgebase/th3d-ezabl-cr-10-sensor-mount/
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2552539

Acknowledgement:

Thank you to Alex of Microswiss for sending out a sample of their all metal hotend

These cleats replaced the original hard rubber cleats found on a 1960s Schwinn. The original rubber cleats were worn and hardened, and would spin too easily around the bolts, causing my foot to slip off the pedals at bad times. They looked nice but were not safe, and soaking them in rubber re-grip didn't help.

These cleats are designed to fit tightly around the center axle and bolts, to distribute pedaling force evenly and also to avoid rattling. I used thick walls and high infill for strength, and supports only to the build plate. Oriented to minimize support material.

My pedals had long bolts and nuts. I see a lot of similar pedals with rivets that look easy to drill out and replace with bolts and nuts. While apart it is a good time to clean and lube the bearings.

Cleats are split in two because the bearing retainers tend to be stamped and not removable, so it would be hard to install as a one-piece whole platform cleat.

title: Ormerod 2 Adapter to fit a Nimble

description.text:
An adapter and reworked E3D V6 mount for on the Ormerod 2 printer.

The adapter holds and centres the Nimble to the hot end and the two parts of the clamp allow for the V6 to be mounted. The rework of the clamps is just to add a bolt hole or a little space for a bolt to stick through the nut.
The Nimble will overhang at the back, roughly 9 mm. This should be OK and the holes for the tie-wraps are still usable.

To be able to print easier, I put a thin wall between the nut space and the bolt hole. After printing, simply drill it out with a 3 mm drill. Also, the Filament hole is covered the same way. This is a 4 mm hole and a 2 mm hole. The reason for the keyhole shape, is so that you can insert a thin rod in the smaller section to push down the collet in the V6 to release the PTFE tube, without needing to take it all apart.

To get the correct PTFE tubing length, install a tube that is a little bit too long, mount the V6 and the adapter. Then slice the PTFE tube off, flush with the top of the adapter. Then mount the Nimble. There will be almost no space between the tube and the base of the Nimble.

The Nimble Extruder

With an installed weight of less than 27 grams on your carriage/effector the Zesty Nimble is smallest and lightest extruder you can buy, it has ample torque and can be mounted in multiple orientations.

The Nimble is available from Zesty Technology.

Check the gallery for step by step instructions. WARNING: Working with molten metal can be FATAL. Exercise safety precautions at all times. Aluminum melts at 1220 degrees F and that means third degree burns if you are careless enough to forget that.

  • 3D scan your face. This scan was done on Next Engine with Scan Studio on high resolution.

  • 3D print the face. Use proper support and carefully clean with needle nose pliers.

  • Vacuum form the results. I vacuum formed the face print with a Formech system.

  • Plaster cast. Mix some plaster of Paris with water to create a negative mold by placing the vacuum form into the liquid plaster. Allow 6 minutes to harden! After that, slowly pinch out the vacuum form and you're ready to pour hot aluminum only after you BAKE your plaster mold. Do not forget to cook your negative mold to evaporate all moisture.

  • Pour molten aluminum. Carefully pour your aluminum into your negative with a reservoir runoff for over pouring. Let cool for 15 minutes~ and spray with water to cool off before touching.

comments.text: Let me know! If acetone works I'd love to see that otherwise vacuum forming isn't necessary. Try anything you have for the mold release but never forget to bake it before you pour your aluminum. If you pour with little pieces of PLA or ABS in your mold they'll release gas and sputter through the molten aluminum like a sprinkler. This is why I'd rather avoid the PLA touching the plaster all together.

description.text: Done in Moray for Windows 3.5 and exported via my scad export plugin. This uses http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3575/#files (parametric involute gears V5 by GregFrost). The general design has been tested in 2/3 (or perhaps 1/2) scale with PLA and a 0.2 mm nozzle, and worked well. Currently printing full-size version after modifying some proportions (thicker frame for strength, thinner gears to make pens work better). Expecting 5-10 print hours at 40 mm feedrate, 0.2 mm nozzle and 0.15 mm layers. The .STL should fit on a replicator dual platform. The .SCAD file is code generated from the current version of my plugin (somewhat larger scale than the .STL), and the .ZIP contains the current version of the Moray plugin and .MDL model file for anyone who wants to edit the model. For those interested, the plugin now allows creation of spur gears in Moray by applying a naming convention to any cylinders that represent gears. On export, the gears are generated in SCAD by linking into GregFrost's parametric gear script.

PLA is highly recommended. I used a 0.2 mm nozzle and a 0.15 mm layer height.   
If you re-export the scad file from Moray, you will need to go through the scad file afterwards, and add "backlash = -0.4" to the 'inside' gears (the ones that get cut out of the frame), and "backlash = 0.2" to the 4 normal gears. This ensures sufficient clearence for the gear teeth.

title: Magnetic trickle charger license plate mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a license plate mount for a magnetic trickle charger connector. The connector is from Magcode. https://www.rosenberger.com/en/products/automotive/magcode.php
You can purchase them on ebay. I went with the 3 piece kit which has the "Power Port" which goes on the car and in this bracket, a cover for the port and then a "Power Clip" which you insert the charger cable into.

There are two style of mounts. One that simply bolts in front of a plate or frame and one that is designed to bolt behind the plate/frame and then encompass the top edge a bit. The latter looks sleeker but requires quite a bit of clearance above (or below if using bottom plate holes) the plate.

This is being used for a trickle charger for my lotus but you could use it for any car that uses a license plate sized for the americas and for any application where you need 12v power at that location.

This is a Halbach NMR Mandhala (along with several attachments) to be used in small magnetic resonance imaging experiments.

The purpose of the Halbach NMR Mandhala [Magnet Arrangements for Novel Discrete Halbach Layout, created by Raich and Blümler, “Design and Construction of a Dipolar Halbach Array with a Homogeneous Field from Identical Bar Magnets: NMR Mandhalas”, Concepts in Magnetic Resonance part B (Magnetic Resonance Engineering), Vol. 23B(1) 16-25 (2004), DOI 10.1002/cmr.b.20018] is to provide a large, homogeneous magnetic field over a large and accessible volume made from identical and affordable permanent magnets. This design focuses on modularity and flexibility to generate a variety of different magnetic fields which can be easily modified depending on desired uses and sample sizes.

There are five individual pieces:

  1. NMR Mandhala
    • 8 cm outer diameter, 4 cm inner diameter
    • Eight 1/2” x 1/2” x 1/2” slots for the permanent magnets (N-52 ½” cubes from K&J Magnetics).Lip on top and bottom so that mandalas can be stacked for a greater field (~0.3 T at center)
  2. Lid
    • 4 cm inner diameter
    • Four holes for bolts (Nylon ¼-20 hex bolt, 3” length)
    • 3.8 cm divot to hold mandalas
  3. Base
    • Four holes for bolts
    • 3.8-cm diameter divot to hold NMR Mandhalas
  4. Sample Holder
    • Five holes to hold 5mm NMR sample test tubes
    • Arms slot into the lid to keep stable
  5. Center Mandhala
    • 4 cm outer diameter, 2 cm inner diameter
    • Eight 1/4” x 1/4” x 1” slots for the permanent magnets (B44X0 N-52 from K&J Magnetics).
    • An additional NMR Mandhala to fit inside two stacked 8-cm Mandhalas to provide a stronger field (up to 0.45 T)

Stacking the Mandhalas can be tricky, as their magnetic fields will want to align in a way that isn't conducive to imaging. Therefore we recommend securing the top Mandhala to the lid and the bottom Mandhala to the base using hot glue. Using other forms of glue would prevent removing the Mandhalas.

The photos include two pictures of all the components stacked (minus the sample holder). Also included are plots of the respective magnetic fields of two Mandhalas we constructed ourselves as well as the plot when they're stacked together. The final photo is a plot of the field of the two stacked magnets when the Middle Mandhala is inserted.

All the files here were made in SketchUp using designs from the article above for the NMR Mandhalas themselves and original designs for the base, sample holder, lid, and center Mandhala. They were converted to .stl files in MeshLab. Theoretical predictions were calculated and plotted using the open-source Finite Element Method Magnetics, FEMM 4.2 and magnetic field measurements were made with AlphaLab’s Gaussmeter Model 2.

This model was constructed by Jeremiah O'Mahony with guidance and good-natured mockery from Merideth Frey, PhD, in beautiful Yonkers, New York.

title: Dog-Proof Cat Feeder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
My Sisters Labrador called Sasha has been getting fat eating the cats food and the poor cats are losing weight :(

Since Sasha is the leading lady in some of my productions I thought I should find a way to help her with her dieting by developing a Dog-Proof Cat Feeder!

I've added a short video showing it in use here:-
https://youtu.be/cVl03hrmBLQ

The early prototype started well but Sasha worked out how to get the loose cap off the top so I then added a secure screw on lid.

The way it works is that dogs (apart from the tiny varieties) have almost double the paw width that cats have and the slots to the cat food are too narrow for a dogs paw but more than enough for a full size tabby. The cats paw out their meal and then more cat food comes down the hopper. Most cats won't overeat so it's generally safe to trust them with there own food.

The hopper can take approximately 8 standard cat meals so if you go away the cats can feed themselves!

The three cats all quickly worked out how to use it and now Sasha can get slim for Summer :D

Now if you want to get real tricky with this print you can print it in a semi-transparent filament so you can see how much cat food is left :)

You can check out my other designs here:-
https://www.thingiverse.com/ScottyMakesStuff/designs

You can see all my videos on my YouTube Channel, ScottyMakesStuff here:-
https://www.youtube.com/channel/UChDeVchB6CCF--0wQQYNIhQ

description.text:
I needed new bumpers on my trucks liftgate but didn't want to pay almost $40 for a set just like the ones that had already came off. So I designed some rounded ones then decided I wanted them to have more of a flat surface for even more support.

Sometimes I pick up full drums from a shop with nice sealed concrete floors so I don't want to damage the floors sealed surface with a bare metal gate scratching the floor surface

A 1.5" OD fender washer fits snugly inside. The bumpers thickness behind the washer is 4mm thick so it's not flimsy.
The OD of the bumper is 70mm = 2.755897"
Bumper height is 16mm = 0.6299194" or about 5/8"

I am including both designs but V2 is the ones I ended up printing and installing.

Notes:

I printed these with a brim, no rafts, and they adhered well to the plate. Scale sizes using your 3D pre-processing software. Vary the stem lengths by rotating the piece to stand upright in your software and then change the z-height while leaving x- and y- dimensions the same. Rotate the stem back down flat to the build plate for easier printing.

I've included leaves with various dimensions.

Assembly

I assembled the pieces using Plastruct Plastic Weld, which works quite effectively for bonding PLA pieces. If you mix materials, it binds ABS and PLA together as well. The leaves are a little tricky to orient because the faces are not completely flush, but they did stay together without too much trouble.
